  <h3>Search tips in non-Arabic characters</h3>
<ul>
<li>Searches you perform on this site will query only the descriptive information about each book, both in English and Arabic, but not the full texts of the books. As searching technologies for Arabic develop, we intend to introduce full-text searching.</li>
<li>Transliteration (for consonants) usually follows the LOC transliteration system.</li>
<li>Vocalization follows Modern Standard Arabic (fuṣḥá).</li>
<li>Diacritical vowels are equivalent to normal characters, i.e. Ḥajjāj = Hajjaj.</li>
<li>Try searching by different transliterations, i.e. Cairo, Qahira, Qahirah, Tehran, Tihran.</li>
<li>Try searching places in English, French, or transliteration, i.e. Egypt, Egypte, Misr.</li>
<li>Try searching subject terms in English, French, or transliteration, i.e. philosophy, philosophie, falsafah.</li>
<li>Try searching names with or without the definite article “Al-“.</li>
<li>Case endings are not included, i.e. search for al-Kabir not al-Kabiru.</li>
<li>Feminine possessive suffix appears as -iyah and not as -iyyah, i.e. search for Hanafiyah.</li>
<li>Tanwīn al-Fatḥ is written in transliteration as -an, i.e. search for khassatan.</li>
<li>Tāʼ Marbūṭah is written as -h for single nouns and -t in cases of al-Iḍāfah (compound nouns).
Click on hyper-linked metadata to find other books in the same category.</li>
<li>Books in multi-volume works appear as separate search results. In the book viewer, click on “view related titles” to read the other volumes.</li></ul>
